# Git Workflow Conventions

## Commit Format (Conventional Commits)

```
type(scope): description

[optional body — explain WHY not WHAT]

[optional footer: Refs #123, Closes #456, BREAKING CHANGE: ...]
```

### Types

| Type | When to Use |
|------|-------------|
| `feat` | New feature or capability |
| `fix` | Bug fix |
| `docs` | Documentation only |
| `style` | Formatting, no logic change |
| `refactor` | Code restructuring, no behavior change |
| `test` | Adding or updating tests |
| `chore` | Build, CI, tooling changes |
| `ci` | CI/CD pipeline changes |
| `perf` | Performance improvement |

### Scopes (IronLayer)

| Scope | Description |
|-------|-------------|
| `plan` | Plan engine |
| `lineage` | Column-level lineage |
| `cost` | Cost modeling |
| `mcp` | MCP server tools |
| `cli` | CLI changes |
| `core_engine` | Deterministic core |
| `ai_engine` | AI advisory layer |

### Examples

```
feat(plan): add column-level impact scoring to execution plan
feat(mcp): add lineage query tool to MCP server
fix(executor): handle Databricks timeout with retry
docs(cli): add CLI reference documentation
test(planner): add interval planning unit tests
```

## Branch Naming

```
feature/<description>   # New features
fix/<issue-description> # Bug fixes
docs/<topic>            # Documentation updates
refactor/<area>         # Code cleanup
```

## PR Guidelines

1. Title follows conventional commit format
2. Description includes: Summary, Test Plan, Checklist
3. All tests must pass
4. Plans must be deterministic — add tests for new planner logic
